What is APR?
yes

APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure of the annual cost of borrowing money, expressed as a percentage rate. This includes not only the interest you pay on loans but also any fees associated with obtaining that loan. APR helps consumers compare different loan offers more accurately because it provides a consistent basis for comparing costs across various lenders and types of loans.

For example, if you're considering two mortgage options, one with an interest rate of 4% and the other with an APR of 4.25%, the latter represents a higher cost due to additional fees. By using APR, you can get a clearer picture of which loan will actually cost more over the course of a year when all costs are taken into account.

APR is typically used for credit cards and loans but can also be applied to other financial products like auto loans or home equity lines of credit. It's important to note that APRs may vary depending on factors such as the loan term, whether it's a fixed or variable rate, and any additional charges.